  "diary": "Started the day right—sunny and warm, so I grabbed my usual espresso at Ladro before heading to the studio. The drive through Ballard was perfect, light traffic. Had two solid sessions today: a regular came in for some detailed line work that felt really clean, and the afternoon color piece turned out beautifully. I caught a few minutes of the USA-Wales match on my phone during setup, though I missed most of it. Grabbed Thai at Revel for lunch and wandered through the vintage mall afterward—found some cool old camera gear I might scout for a shoot. On the way home, I stopped by the water to catch the sunset and ran through some film. Nothing fancy, just golden hour stuff, but it felt necessary after a full day. Spent the evening in the darkroom, developing prints, then sat on the porch with tea watching them dry. There's something about a day that moves this smoothly—work that matters, light that cooperates, no transit drama.",
  "thought_process": "The light rail closure didn't touch me since I drive to Fremont anyway, which was lucky. The sunny weather just set a good tone from the jump—made me want to move, shoot, be present. I took the scenic route through Ballard twice because I had the time and the light was worth it. The World Cup buzz downtown was happening, but I'm not really invested in soccer, so that was background noise. What pulled my attention was how the two tattoo sessions flowed—the morning line work felt meditative, and the afternoon color piece let me experiment with some new shading techniques I've been thinking about. The film photography broke up the day nicely, kept me from getting too locked into the chair. By evening I was genuinely eager to develop those sunset shots, which tells me I needed that creative outlet today.",
